{
  "id": "pl19",
  "type": "plotlines",
  "name": "Children's Book Plot",
  "description": "An outline formula for writing books for children",
  "version": "2021.8.26",
  "categories": [
    "children"
  ],
  "templateData": {
    "cards": [
      {
        "id": 7,
        "lineId": 1,
        "beatId": 8,
        "bookId": null,
        "positionWithinLine": 0,
        "positionInBeat": 0,
        "title": "Resolution",
        "description": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "--- Add Your Details Above this Line ---"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "End of Act 3:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Using all they have learned, the Protagonist works to find another solution, which is finally successful. The story's Resolution must be driven by the Protagonist, not an adult."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Let the Protagonist come to the solution on their own – for example, in a moment of reflection, with the help of friends, or by an idea triggered by an object or something else in the vicinity."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Use all they have learned to solve the problem."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Show the Protagonist enjoying the fruits of their labors and how they have changed."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Wrap up storylines and character arcs now that the problem has been solved."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Example:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "As the girls get to the bottom of the stairs in the basement, they hear Amala's dog barking and growling at something. They run into the playroom and find the dog in its bed playing with Amala's boots! Apparently it had taken the boots from the top of the stairs. Amala runs over and hugs the dog as Carolina saves the boots. They then run upstairs and go outside to play, while Amala promises herself and Carolina that she'll keep her boots in her closet from now on."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "Breakdown:",
                "bold": true
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "bulleted-list",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Act 3 makes up the final 25% of the story."
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "list-item",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "text": "Resolution occurs around the 90% mark."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
